# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: race-condition-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Systems implement locking to prevent an *interceding update* scenario, which is an example of a race condition, by enforcing the serialization of update processes to any given file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Process B now reads the same record from the same file, so it has its own copy.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Process A changes the account balance in its copy of the customer record and writes the record back to the file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Process B, which still has the original *stale* value for the account balance in its copy of the customer record, updates the account balance and writes the customer record back to the file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Process B has now written its stale account-balance value to the file, causing the changes made by process A to be lost.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Most operating systems support the concept of record locking, which means that individual records within any given file may be locked, thereby increasing the number of concurrent update processes.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Database maintenance uses file locking, whereby it can serialize access to the entire physical file underlying a database.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Although this does prevent any other process from accessing the file, it can be more efficient than individually locking many regions in the file by removing the overhead of acquiring and releasing each lock.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Poor use of file locks, like any computer lock, can result in poor performance or in deadlocks.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] File locking may also refer to additional security applied by a computer user either by using Windows security, NTFS permissions or by installing a third party file locking software.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] IBM pioneered file locking in 1963 for use in mainframe computers using OS/360, where it was termed "exclusive control".
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Windows inherits the semantics of share-access controls from the MS-DOS system, where sharing was introduced in MS-DOS 3.3 .
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For a file opened with shared access, applications may then use byte-range locking to control access to specific regions of the file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Such byte-range locks specify a region of the file (offset and length) and the type of lock (shared or exclusive).
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Note that the region of the file being locked is *not* required to have data within the file, and applications sometimes exploit this ability to implement their functionality.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For applications that use the file read/write APIs in Windows, byte-range locks are enforced (also referred to as *mandatory locks*) by the file systems that execute within Windows.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For applications that use the file mapping APIs in Windows, byte-range locks are not enforced (also referred to as *advisory locks.*) Byte-range locking may also have other side-effects on the Windows system.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For example, the Windows file-sharing mechanism will typically disable client side caching of a file for *all* clients when byte-range locks are used by *any* client.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The client will observe slower access because read and write operations must be sent to the server where the file is stored.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Improper error-handling in an application program can lead to a scenario where a file is locked (either using "share" access or with byte-range file locking) and cannot be accessed by other applications.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] If so, the user may be able to restore file access by manually terminating the malfunctioning program.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This is typically done through the Task Manager utility.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The *sharing mode* (dwShareMode) parameter of the `CreateFile` function (used to open files) determines file-sharing.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The sharing mode can be specified to allow sharing the file for read, write, or delete access, or any combination of these.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Subsequent attempts to open the file must be compatible with all previously granted sharing-access to the file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] When the file is closed, sharing-access restrictions are adjusted to remove the restrictions imposed by that specific file open.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Byte-range locking type is determined by the *`dwFlags`* parameter in the `LockFileEx` function used to lock a region of a file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The Windows API function `LockFile` can also be used and acquires an exclusive lock on the region of the file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Any file containing an executable program file that is currently running on the computer system as a program (e.g. an `EXE`, `COM`, `DLL`, `CPL` or other binary program file format) is normally locked by the operating system itself, preventing any application from modifying or deleting it.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Any attempt to do so will be denied with a sharing violation error, despite the fact that the program file is not opened by any application.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For example, a running application file can be renamed or copied (read) even when executing.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Files are accessed by applications in Windows by using *file handles*.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] These file handles can be explored with the Process Explorer utility.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This utility can also be used to force-close handles without needing to terminate the application holding them.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This can cause an undefined behavior, since the program will receive an unexpected error when using the force-closed handle and may even operate on an unexpected file since the handle number may be recycled.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Microsoft Windows XP and Server 2003 editions have introduced volume snapshot (`VSS`) capability to NTFS, allowing open files to be accessed by backup software despite any exclusive locks.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] However, unless software is rewritten to specifically support this feature, the snapshot will be *crash consistent* only, while properly supported applications can assist the operating system in creating "transactionally consistent" snapshots.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Other commercial software for accessing locked files under Windows include File Access Manager and Open File Manager.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] These work by installing their own drivers to access the files in kernel mode.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Unix-like operating systems (including Linux and Apple's macOS) do not normally automatically lock open files.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Several kinds of file-locking mechanisms are available in different flavors of Unix, and many operating systems support more than one kind for compatibility.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Two other such mechanisms are `flock(2)` and `lockf(3)`, each of which may be implemented atop `fcntl` or may be implemented separately from `fcntl`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Although some types of locks can be configured to be mandatory, file locks under Unix are by default *advisory*.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This means that cooperating processes may use locks to coordinate access to a file among themselves, but uncooperative processes are also free to ignore locks and access the file in any way they choose.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] In other words, file locks lock out other file lockers only, not I/O.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Two kinds of locks are offered: shared locks and exclusive locks.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] In the case of `fcntl`, different kinds of locks may be applied to different sections (byte ranges) of a file, or else to the whole file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Shared locks can be held by multiple processes at the same time, but an exclusive lock can only be held by one process, and cannot coexist with a shared lock.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] To acquire a shared lock, a process must wait until no processes hold any exclusive locks.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] To acquire an exclusive lock, a process must wait until no processes hold either kind of lock.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Unlike locks created by `fcntl`, those created by `flock` are preserved across `fork`s, making them useful in forking servers.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] It is therefore possible for more than one process to hold an exclusive lock on the same file, provided these processes share a filial relationship and the exclusive lock was initially created in a single process before being duplicated across a `fork`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Shared locks are sometimes called "read locks" and exclusive locks are sometimes called "write locks".
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] However, because locks on Unix are advisory, this isn't enforced.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Thus it is possible for a database to have a concept of "shared writes" vs.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] "exclusive writes"; for example, changing a field in place may be permitted under shared access, whereas garbage-collecting and rewriting the database may require exclusive access.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] File locks apply to the actual file, rather than the file name.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This is important since Unix allows multiple names to refer to the same file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Together with non-mandatory locking, this leads to great flexibility in accessing files from multiple processes.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] On the other hand, the cooperative locking approach can lead to problems when a process writes to a file without obeying file locks set by other processes.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For this reason, some Unix-like operating systems also offer limited support for *mandatory locking*.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] On such systems, a file whose `setgid` bit is on but whose group execution bit is off when that file is opened will be subject to automatic mandatory locking if the underlying filesystem supports it.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] However, non-local NFS partitions tend to disregard this bit.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] If a file is subject to mandatory locking, attempts to read from a region that is locked with an exclusive lock, or to write to a region that is locked with a shared or exclusive lock, will block until the lock is released.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This strategy first originated in System V, and can be seen today in the Solaris, HP-UX, and Linux operating systems.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] It is not part of POSIX, however, and BSD-derived operating systems such as FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD, and Apple's macOS do not support it.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Linux also supports *mandatory locking* through the special *`-o mand`* parameter for file system mounting (`mount(8)`), but this is rarely used.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Some Unix-like operating systems prevent attempts to open the executable file of a running program for writing; this is a third form of locking, separate from those provided by `fcntl` and `flock`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] More than one process can hold an exclusive `flock` on a given file if the exclusive lock was duplicated across a later `fork`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This simplifies coding for network servers and helps prevent race conditions, but can be confusing to the unaware.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Mandatory locks have no effect on `unlink`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Consequently, certain programs may, effectively, circumvent mandatory locking.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Stevens & Rago (2005) observed that the `ed` editor indeed did that.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Whether and how `flock` locks work on network filesystems, such as NFS, is implementation dependent.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] On BSD systems, `flock` calls on a file descriptor open to a file on an NFS-mounted partition are successful no-ops.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] On Linux prior to 2.6.12, `flock` calls on NFS files would act only locally.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Kernel 2.6.12 and above implement `flock` calls on NFS files using POSIX byte-range locks.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] These locks will be visible to other NFS clients that implement `fcntl`-style *POSIX locks*, but invisible to those that do not.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Lock upgrades and downgrades *release* the old lock before applying the new lock.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] If an application downgrades an exclusive lock to a shared lock while another application is blocked waiting for an exclusive lock, the latter application may get the exclusive lock and lock the first application out.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This means that lock downgrades can block, which may be counter-intuitive.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Preservation of the lock status on open file descriptors passed to another process using a Unix domain socket is implementation dependent.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] One source of lock failure occurs when buffered I/O has buffers assigned in the user's local workspace, rather than in an operating system buffer pool.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] `fread` and `fwrite` are commonly used to do buffered I/O, and once a section of a file is read, another attempt to read that same section will, most likely, obtain the data from the local buffer.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The problem is another user attached to the same file has their own local buffers, and the same thing is happening for them.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] An `fwrite` of data obtained from the buffer by `fread` will ***not*** be obtaining the data from the file itself, and some other user could have changed it.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Both could use `flock` to ensure exclusive access, which prevents simultaneous writes, but since the reads are reading from the buffer and not the file itself, any data changed by user #1 can be lost by user #2 (over-written).
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The best solution to this problem is to use unbuffered I/O (`read` and `write`) with `flock`, which also means using `lseek` instead of `fseek` and `ftell`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Of course, you'll have to make adjustments for function parameters and results returned.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Generally speaking, buffered I/O is *unsafe* when used with shared files.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] In AmigaOS, a lock on a file (or directory) can be acquired using the `Lock` function (in the `dos.library`).
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] A lock can be shared (other processes can read the file/directory, but can't modify or delete it), or exclusive so that only the process which successfully acquires the lock can access or modify the object.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The lock is on the whole object and not part of it.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] The lock must be released with the `UnLock` function: unlike in Unix, the operating system does not implicitly unlock the object when the process terminates.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] A lock file is often the best approach if the resource to be controlled is not a regular file at all, so using methods for locking files does not apply.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] For example, a lock file might govern access to a set of related resources, such as several different files, directories, a group of disk partitions, or selected access to higher level protocols like servers or database connections.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] When using lock files, care must be taken to ensure that operations are atomic.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] To obtain a lock, the process must verify that the lock file does not exist and then create it, whilst preventing another process from creating it in the meantime.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Lock files are often named with a tilde (`~`) prefixed to the name of the file they are locking, or a duplicate of the full file name suffixed with `.LCK` .
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] If they are locking a resource other than a file, they may be named more arbitrarily.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] An unlocker is a utility used to determine what process is locking a file, and displays a list of processes as well as choices on what to do with the process (kill task, unlock, etc.) along with a list of file options such as delete or rename.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Their purpose is to remove improper or stale file locks, which often arise from anomalous situations, such as crashed or hung processes, that lead to file locks that persist despite the owning process having died already.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] On some Unix-like systems, utilities such as `fstat` and `lockf` can be used to inspect the state of file locks by process, by filename, or both.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] On Windows systems, if a file is locked, it's possible to schedule its moving or deletion to be performed on the next reboot.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This approach is typically used by installers to replace locked system files.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] In version control systems file locking is used to prevent two users changing the same file version in parallel and then when saving, the second user to overwrite what first user changed.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] This is implemented by marking locked files as read-only in the file system.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] A user wanting to change the file performs an unlock (also called checkout) operation, and until a check-in (store) operation is done, or the lock is reverted, nobody else is allowed to unlock the file.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] Rust supports file locking using the `lock`, `try_lock`, `lock_shared`, `try_lock_shared` and `unlock` methods.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] .NET supports file locking using a `FileStream`.
[src:race-condition-security/file-locking] PHP supports file locking using the `flock` function.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:race-condition-security/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] That sequential history is a subset of the original unextended list.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Informally, this means that the unmodified list of events is linearizable if and only if its invocations were serializable, but some of the responses of the serial schedule have yet to return.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In a concurrent system, processes can access a shared object at the same time.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Because multiple processes are accessing a single object, a situation may arise in which while one process is accessing the object, another process changes its contents.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Making a system linearizable is one solution to this problem.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In a linearizable system, although operations overlap on a shared object, each operation appears to take place instantaneously.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Linearizability is a strong correctness condition, which constrains what outputs are possible when an object is accessed by multiple processes concurrently.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] It is a safety property which ensures that operations do not complete unexpectedly or unpredictably.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] If a system is linearizable it allows a programmer to reason about the system.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Linearizability was first introduced as a consistency model by Herlihy and Wing in 1987.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] It encompassed more restrictive definitions of atomic, such as "an atomic operation is one which cannot be (or is not) interrupted by concurrent operations", which are usually vague about when an operation is considered to begin and end.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] An atomic object can be understood immediately and completely from its sequential definition, as a set of operations run in parallel which always appear to occur one after the other; no inconsistencies may emerge.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Specifically, linearizability guarantees that the invariants of a system are *observed* and *preserved* by all operations: if all operations individually preserve an invariant, the system as a whole will.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] A concurrent system consists of a collection of processes communicating through shared data structures or objects.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Linearizability is important in these concurrent systems where objects may be accessed by multiple processes at the same time and a programmer needs to be able to reason about the expected results.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] An execution of a concurrent system results in a *history*, an ordered sequence of completed operations.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] A *history* is a sequence of *invocations* and *responses* made of an object by a set of threads or processes.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] An invocation can be thought of as the start of an operation, and the response being the signaled end of that operation.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Each invocation of a function will have a subsequent response.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This can be used to model any use of an object.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Suppose, for example, that two threads, A and B, both attempt to grab a lock, backing off if it's already taken.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This would be modeled as both threads invoking the lock operation, then both threads receiving a response, one successful, one not.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] A *sequential* history is one in which all invocations have immediate responses; that is the invocation and response are considered to take place instantaneously.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] A sequential history should be trivial to reason about, as it has no real concurrency; the previous example was not sequential, and thus is hard to reason about.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] If an operation op1 completes (gets a response) before op2 begins (invokes), then op1 precedes op2 in $\sigma$ .
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Note that the first two bullet points here match serializability: the operations appear to happen in some order.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] It is the last point which is unique to linearizability, and is thus the major contribution of Herlihy and Wing.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Consider two ways of reordering the locking example above.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Reordering B's invocation after A's response yields a sequential history.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This is easy to reason about, as all operations now happen in an obvious order.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] However, it does not match the sequential definition of the object (it doesn't match the semantics of the program): A should have successfully obtained the lock, and B should have subsequently aborted.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This is another correct sequential history.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] It is also a linearization since it matches the sequential definition.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Note that the definition of linearizability only precludes responses that precede invocations from being reordered; since the original history had no responses before invocations, they can be reordered.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Hence the original history is indeed linearizable.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] An object (as opposed to a history) is linearizable if all valid histories of its use can be linearized.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This is a much harder assertion to prove.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This history is not valid because there is a point at which both A and B hold the lock; moreover, it cannot be reordered to a valid sequential history without violating the ordering rule.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This reordering is sensible provided there is no alternative means of communicating between A and B.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Linearizability is better when considering individual objects separately, as the reordering restrictions ensure that multiple linearizable objects are, considered as a whole, still linearizable.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This alternative is usually much easier to prove.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] It is also much easier to reason about as a user, largely due to its intuitiveness.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This property of occurring instantaneously, or indivisibly, leads to the use of the term *atomic* as an alternative to the longer "linearizable".
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In the examples below, the linearization point of the counter built on compare-and-swap is the linearization point of the first (and only) successful compare-and-swap update.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The counter built using locking can be considered to linearize at any moment while the locks are held, since any potentially conflicting operations are excluded from running during that period.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Processors have instructions that can be used to implement locking and lock-free and wait-free algorithms.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The ability to temporarily inhibit interrupts, ensuring that the currently running process cannot be context switched, also suffices on a uniprocessor.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Most processors include store operations that are not atomic with respect to memory.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] These include multiple-word stores and string operations.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Should a high priority interrupt occur when a portion of the store is complete, the operation must be completed when the interrupt level is returned.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The routine that processes the interrupt must not modify the memory being changed.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] It is important to take this into account when writing interrupt routines.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] When there are multiple instructions which must be completed without interruption, a CPU instruction which temporarily disables interrupts is used.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This must be kept to only a few instructions and the interrupts must be re-enabled to avoid unacceptable response time to interrupts or even losing interrupts.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This mechanism is not sufficient in a multi-processor environment since each CPU can interfere with the process regardless of whether interrupts occur or not.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Further, in the presence of an instruction pipeline, uninterruptible operations present a security risk, as they can potentially be chained in an infinite loop to create a denial of service attack, as in the Cyrix coma bug.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The C standard and SUSv3 provide `sig_atomic_t` for simple atomic reads and writes; incrementing or decrementing is not guaranteed to be atomic.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] More complex atomic operations are available in C11, which provides `stdatomic.h`.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Compilers use the hardware features or more complex methods to implement the operations; an example is libatomic of GCC.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The ARM instruction set provides `LDREX` and `STREX` instructions which can be used to implement atomic memory access by using exclusive monitors implemented in the processor to track memory accesses for a specific address.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] However, if a context switch occurs between calls to `LDREX` and `STREX`, the documentation notes that `STREX` will fail, indicating the operation should be retried.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In the case of 64-bit ARMv8-A architecture, it provides `LDXR` and `STXR` instructions for byte, half-word, word, and double-word size.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The easiest way to achieve linearizability is running groups of primitive operations in a critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Strictly, independent operations can then be carefully permitted to overlap their critical sections, provided this does not violate linearizability.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Such an approach must balance the cost of large numbers of locks against the benefits of increased parallelism.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Another approach, favoured by researchers (but not yet widely used in the software industry), is to design a linearizable object using the native atomic primitives provided by the hardware.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This has the potential to maximise available parallelism and minimise synchronisation costs, but requires mathematical proofs which show that the objects behave correctly.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] A promising hybrid of these two is to provide a transactional memory abstraction.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] As with critical sections, the user marks sequential code that must be run in isolation from other threads.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The implementation then ensures the code executes atomically.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This style of abstraction is common when interacting with databases; for instance, when using the Spring Framework, annotating a method with @Transactional will ensure all enclosed database interactions occur in a single database transaction.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Transactional memory goes a step further, ensuring that all memory interactions occur atomically.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] As with database transactions, issues arise regarding composition of transactions, especially database and in-memory transactions.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] A common theme when designing linearizable objects is to provide an all-or-nothing interface: either an operation succeeds completely, or it fails and does nothing.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] (ACID databases refer to this principle as atomicity.) If the operation fails (usually due to concurrent operations), the user must retry, usually performing a different operation.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] To demonstrate the power and necessity of linearizability we will consider a simple counter which different processes can increment.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] We would like to implement a counter object which multiple processes can access.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Many common systems make use of counters to keep track of the number of times an event has occurred.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The counter object can be accessed by multiple processes and has two available operations.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Read - returns the current value stored in the counter without changing it.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] We will attempt to implement this counter object using shared registers.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Our first attempt which we will see is non-linearizable has the following implementation using one shared register among the processes.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This simple implementation is not linearizable, as is demonstrated by the following example.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The second process writes the new value into the register, the register now has value 1.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In the above example, two processes invoked an increment command, however the value of the object only increased from 0 to 1, instead of 2 as it should have.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] One of the increment operations was lost as a result of the system not being linearizable.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The above example shows the need for carefully thinking through implementations of data structures and how linearizability can have an effect on the correctness of the system.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] To implement a linearizable or atomic counter object we will modify our previous implementation so **each process Pi will use its own register Ri**.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This is similar to how grow-only counter CRDTs work.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This implementation solves the problem with our original implementation.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In this system the increment operations are linearized at the write step.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The linearization point of an increment operation is when that operation writes the new value in its register Ri.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] The read operations are linearized to a point in the system when the value returned by the read is equal to the sum of all the values stored in each register Ri.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] In a real system, the operations can be more complex and the errors introduced extremely subtle.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] For example, reading a 64-bit value from memory may actually be implemented as two sequential reads of two 32-bit memory locations.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] If a process has only read the first 32 bits, and before it reads the second 32 bits the value in memory gets changed, it will have neither the original value nor the new value but a mixed-up value.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Furthermore, the specific order in which the processes run can change the results, making such an error difficult to detect, reproduce and debug.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Most systems provide an atomic compare-and-swap instruction that reads from a memory location, compares the value with an "expected" one provided by the user, and writes out a "new" value if the two match, returning whether the update succeeded.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] 4. retry if the value read in by the compare-and-swap did not match the value we originally read.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Since the compare-and-swap occurs (or appears to occur) instantaneously, if another process updates the location while we are in-progress, the compare-and-swap is guaranteed to fail.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Many systems provide an atomic fetch-and-increment instruction that reads from a memory location, unconditionally writes a new value (the old value plus one), and returns the old value.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] So CPU designs with both fetch-and-increment and compare-and-swap (or equivalent instructions) may be a better choice than ones with only one or the other.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] Another approach is to turn the naive algorithm into a critical section, preventing other threads from disrupting it, using a lock.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] This strategy works as expected; the lock prevents other threads from updating the value until it is released.
[src:race-condition-security/linearizability] However, when compared with direct use of atomic operations, it can suffer from significant overhead due to lock contention.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] In computer science, **mutual exclusion** is a property of concurrency control, which is instituted for the purpose of preventing race conditions.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] It is the requirement that one thread of execution never enters a critical section while a concurrent thread of execution is already accessing said critical section, which refers to an interval of time during which a thread of execution accesses a shared resource or shared memory.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The shared resource is a data object, which two or more concurrent threads are trying to modify (where two concurrent read operations are permitted but, no two concurrent write operations or one read and one write are permitted, since it leads to data inconsistency).
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The requirement of mutual exclusion was first identified and solved by Edsger W.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Dijkstra in his seminal 1965 paper "Solution of a problem in concurrent programming control", which is credited as the first topic in the study of concurrent algorithms.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] A simple example of why mutual exclusion is important in practice can be visualized using a singly linked list of four items, where the second and third are to be removed.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Although both removal operations complete successfully, the desired state of the linked list is not achieved: node *i* + 1 remains in the list, because the *next* pointer of node *i* – 1 points to node *i* + 1.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] This problem (called a *race condition*) can be avoided by using the requirement of mutual exclusion to ensure that simultaneous updates to the same part of the list cannot occur.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The term mutual exclusion is also used in reference to the simultaneous writing of a memory address by one thread while the aforementioned memory address is being manipulated or read by one or more other threads.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The problem which mutual exclusion addresses is a problem of resource sharing: how can a software system control multiple processes' access to a shared resource, when each process needs exclusive control of that resource while doing its work?
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The mutual-exclusion solution to this makes the shared resource available only while the process is in a specific code segment called the critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] It controls access to the shared resource by controlling each mutual execution of that part of its program where the resource would be used.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Every process's program can be partitioned into four sections, resulting in four states.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Operation is outside the critical section; the process is not using or requesting the shared resource.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The process attempts to enter the critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The process is allowed to access the shared resource in this section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The process leaves the critical section and makes the shared resource available to other processes.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] If a process wishes to enter the critical section, it must first execute the trying section and wait until it acquires access to the critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] After the process has executed its critical section and is finished with the shared resources, it needs to execute the exit section to release them for other processes' use.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The process then returns to its non-critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] On uni-processor systems, the simplest solution to achieve mutual exclusion is to disable interrupts during a process's critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] This will prevent any interrupt service routines from running (effectively preventing a process from being preempted).
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Although this solution is effective, it leads to many problems.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] If a critical section is long, then the system clock will drift every time a critical section is executed because the timer interrupt is no longer serviced, so tracking time is impossible during the critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Also, if a process halts during its critical section, control will never be returned to another process, effectively halting the entire system.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] A more elegant method for achieving mutual exclusion is the busy-wait.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Busy-waiting is effective for both uniprocessor and multiprocessor systems.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] The use of shared memory and an atomic test-and-set instruction provide the mutual exclusion.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] A process can test-and-set on a location in shared memory, and since the operation is atomic, only one process can set the flag at a time.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Any process that is unsuccessful in setting the flag can either go on to do other tasks and try again later, release the processor to another process and try again later, or continue to loop while checking the flag until it is successful in acquiring it.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Preemption is still possible, so this method allows the system to continue to function—even if a process halts while holding the lock.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Several other atomic operations can be used to provide mutual exclusion of data structures; most notable of these is compare-and-swap (CAS).
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] CAS can be used to achieve wait-free mutual exclusion for any shared data structure by creating a linked list where each node represents the desired operation to be performed.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] CAS is then used to change the pointers in the linked list during the insertion of a new node.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Only one process can be successful in its CAS; all other processes attempting to add a node at the same time will have to try again.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Each process can then keep a local copy of the data structure, and upon traversing the linked list, can perform each operation from the list on its local copy.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] In addition to hardware-supported solutions, some software solutions exist that use busy waiting to achieve mutual exclusion.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] These algorithms do not work if out-of-order execution is used on the platform that executes them.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Programmers have to specify strict ordering on the memory operations within a thread.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] It is often preferable to use synchronization facilities provided by an operating system’s multithreading library, which can take advantage of hardware support when available but fall back on software mechanisms when necessary.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] As a result, most modern mutual exclusion techniques aim to reduce latency and busy-waiting by relying on queuing and context switching.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] However, if the overhead of suspending and later restoring a thread is demonstrably greater than the time the thread would spend waiting for the lock to become available in a specific scenario, then spinlocks can be an acceptable solution in that context.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] One binary test&set register is sufficient to provide the deadlock-free solution to the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] But a solution built with a test&set register can possibly lead to the starvation of some processes which become caught in the trying section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] In fact, $\Omega ({\sqrt {n}})$ distinct memory states are required to avoid lockout.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] To avoid unbounded waiting, *n* distinct memory states are required.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Most algorithms for mutual exclusion are designed with the assumption that no failure occurs while a process is running inside the critical section.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] However, in reality such failures may be commonplace.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] For example, a sudden loss of power or faulty interconnect might cause a process in a critical section to experience an unrecoverable error or otherwise be unable to continue.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] If such a failure occurs, conventional, non-failure-tolerant mutual exclusion algorithms may deadlock or otherwise fail key liveness properties.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] To deal with this problem, several solutions using crash-recovery mechanisms have been proposed.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Many forms of mutual exclusion have side-effects.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] For example, classic semaphores permit deadlocks, in which one process gets a semaphore, another process gets a second semaphore, and then both wait till the other semaphore to be released.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Other common side-effects include starvation, in which a process never gets sufficient resources to run to completion; priority inversion, in which a higher-priority thread waits for a lower-priority thread; and high latency, in which response to interrupts is not prompt.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Much research is aimed at eliminating the above effects, often with the goal of guaranteeing non-blocking progress.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Blocking system calls used to sleep an entire process.
[src:race-condition-security/mutual-exclusion] Until such calls became threadsafe, there was no proper mechanism for sleeping a single thread within a process (see polling).
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A **race condition** or **race hazard** is the condition of an electronics, software, or other system where the system's substantive behavior is dependent on the sequence or timing of uncontrollable events, leading to unexpected or inconsistent results.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] It becomes a bug when one or more of the possible behaviors is undesirable.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The term *race condition* was in use by 1954, for example in David A.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Huffman's doctoral thesis "The synthesis of sequential switching circuits".
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Race conditions can occur especially in logic circuits or concurrent or distributed software programs.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Using mutual exclusion can prevent race conditions.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A typical example of a race condition may occur when a logic gate combines signals that have traveled along different paths from the same source.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The inputs to the gate can change at slightly different times in response to a change in the source signal.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The output may, for a brief period, change to an unwanted state before settling back to the designed state.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Certain systems can tolerate such glitches, but if this output functions as a clock signal for further systems that contain memory, for example, the system can rapidly depart from its designed behaviour (in effect, the temporary glitch becomes a permanent glitch).
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Consider, for example, a two-input AND gate fed with the following logic: ${\text{output}}=A\wedge {\overline {A}}$ A logic signal A on one input and its Boolean negation ${\bar {A}}$ on another input can never, in theory, output a true value as $A\wedge {\overline {A}}\neq 1$ .
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] If, however, changes in the value of A take longer to propagate to the second input than the first when A changes from false to true then a brief period will ensue during which both inputs are true, and so the gate's output will also be true.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A practical example of a race condition can occur when logic circuitry is used to detect certain outputs of a counter.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] If all the bits of the counter do not change exactly simultaneously, there will be intermediate patterns that can trigger false matches.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A *critical race condition* occurs when the order in which internal variables are changed determines the eventual state that the state machine will end up in.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A *non-critical race condition* occurs when the order in which internal variables are changed does not determine the eventual state that the state machine will end up in.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A *static race condition* occurs when a signal and its complement are combined.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A *dynamic race condition* occurs when it results in multiple transitions when only one is intended.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] They are due to interaction between gates.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] It can be eliminated by using no more than two levels of gating.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] An *essential race condition* occurs when an input has two transitions in less than the total feedback propagation time.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Sometimes they are cured using inductive delay line elements to effectively increase the time duration of an input signal.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Design techniques such as Karnaugh maps encourage designers to recognize and eliminate race conditions before they cause problems.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] By simplifying Boolean expressions and analyzing the relationships between input variables, designers can reduce the likelihood of unintended signal changes that may lead to race conditions.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In many cases, logic redundancy can be intentionally added to digital circuits to eliminate certain types of races.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Although redundancy increases the number of logic gates, it can stabilize signal transitions and prevent temporary glitches that occur when signals change at slightly different times.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Engineers may also apply careful timing control and synchronization methods in sequential circuits.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] For example, using clocked elements such as flip-flops can help ensure that signals change in a predictable manner, reducing the risk of race conditions in complex digital systems.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Despite these precautions, some logic elements may still enter metastable states.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In such cases, a circuit temporarily remains in an unstable condition between logical states, which can propagate uncertain signals through the system and create additional challenges for circuit designers.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A race condition can arise in software when a computer program has multiple code paths that are executing at the same time.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] If the multiple code paths take a different amount of time than expected, they can finish in a different order than expected, which can cause software bugs due to unanticipated behavior.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A race can also occur between two programs, resulting in security issues.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Critical race conditions cause invalid execution and software bugs and often happen when processes or threads depend on some shared state.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Operations upon shared states are done in critical sections that must be mutually exclusive.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Failure to obey this rule can corrupt the shared state.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A data race is a type of race condition.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Data races are important parts of various formal memory models.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The memory model defined in the C11 and C++11 standards specify that a C or C++ program containing a data race has undefined behavior.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A race condition can be difficult to reproduce and debug because the result is nondeterministic and depends on the relative timing between interfering threads.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Problems of this nature can therefore disappear when running in debug mode, adding extra logging, or attaching a debugger.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A bug that disappears like this during debugging attempts is often referred to as a *Heisenbug*.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] It is therefore better to avoid race conditions by careful software design.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Assume that two threads each increment the value of a global integer variable by 1.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In the case shown above, the final value is 2, as expected.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] However, if the two threads run simultaneously without locking or synchronization (via semaphores), the outcome of the operation could be wrong.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In this case, the final value is 1 instead of the expected result of 2.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This occurs because here the increment operations are not mutually exclusive.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Mutually exclusive operations are those that cannot be interrupted while accessing some resource such as a memory location.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Not everyone regards data races as a subset of race conditions.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This implies that a data race is different from a race condition as it is possible to have nondeterminism due to timing even in a program without data races, for example, in a program in which all memory accesses use only atomic operations.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] On many platforms, special memory operations are provided for simultaneous access; in such cases, typically simultaneous access using these special operations is safe, but simultaneous access using other memory operations is dangerous.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Sometimes such special operations (which are safe for simultaneous access) are called *atomic* or *synchronization* operations, whereas the ordinary operations (which are unsafe for simultaneous access) are called *data* operations.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This is probably why the term is *data* race; on many platforms, where there is a race condition involving only *synchronization* operations, such a race may be nondeterministic but otherwise safe; but a *data* race could lead to memory corruption or undefined behavior.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The precise definition of data race differs across formal concurrency models.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This matters because concurrent behavior is often non-intuitive and so formal reasoning is sometimes applied.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The parts of this definition relating to signal handlers are idiosyncratic to C++ and are not typical of definitions of *data race*.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Here we have two memory operations accessing the same location, one of which is a write.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] If neither "X happens-before Y" nor "Y happens-before X", then we say that X and Y are "not ordered by the hb1 relation".
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] So, the clause "... and they are not ordered by the hb1 relation of the execution" can be intuitively translated as "... and X and Y are potentially concurrent".
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The paper considers dangerous only those situations in which at least one of the memory operations is a *data operation*; in other parts of this paper, the paper also defines a class of *synchronization operations* which are safe for potentially simultaneous use, in contrast to *data operations*.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A critical difference between the C++ approach and the Java approach is that in C++, a data race is undefined behavior, whereas in Java, a data race merely affects *inter-thread actions*.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] An important facet of data races is that in some contexts, a program that is free of data races is guaranteed to execute in a sequentially consistent manner, greatly easing reasoning about the concurrent behavior of the program.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Formal memory models that provide such a guarantee are said to exhibit an SC for DRF (*sequential consistency for data race freedom*) property.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This approach has been said to have achieved recent consensus (presumably compared to approaches that guarantee sequential consistency in all cases, or approaches which do not guarantee it at all).
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In other words, in C++, some correct programs are not sequentially consistent.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This approach is thought to give C++ programmers the freedom to choose faster program execution at the cost of giving up ease of reasoning about their program.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] There are various theorems, often provided in the form of memory models, that provide SC for DRF guarantees given various contexts.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The DRF1 memory model provides SC for DRF and allows the optimizations of the WO (weak ordering), RCsc (release consistency with sequentially consistent special operations), VAX memory model, and data-race-free-0 memory models.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] The PLpc memory model provides SC for DRF and allows the optimizations of the TSO (total store order), PSO, PC (processor consistency), and RCpc (release consistency with processor consistency special operations) models.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] DRFrlx provides a sketch of an SC for DRF theorem in the presence of relaxed atomics.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Many software race conditions have associated computer security implications.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A race condition allows an attacker with access to a shared resource to cause other actors that utilize that resource to malfunction, resulting in effects including denial of service and privilege escalation.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A specific kind of race condition involves checking for a predicate (e.g. for authentication), then acting on the predicate, while the state can change between the *time-of-check* and the *time-of-use*.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] When this kind of bug exists in security-sensitive code, a security vulnerability called a time-of-check to time-of-use (*TOCTTOU*) bug is created.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Race conditions are also intentionally used to create hardware random number generators and physically unclonable functions.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] PUFs can be created by designing circuit topologies with identical paths to a node and relying on manufacturing variations to randomly determine which paths will complete first.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] By measuring each manufactured circuit's specific set of race condition outcomes, a profile can be collected for each circuit and kept secret in order to later verify a circuit's identity.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Two or more programs may collide in their attempts to modify or access a file system, which can result in data corruption or privilege escalation.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] File locking provides a commonly used solution.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A more cumbersome remedy involves organizing the system in such a way that one unique process (running a daemon or the like) has exclusive access to the file, and all other processes that need to access the data in that file do so only via interprocess communication with that one process.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This requires synchronization at the process level.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A different form of race condition exists in file systems where unrelated programs may affect each other by suddenly using up available resources such as disk space, memory space, or processor cycles.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Software not carefully designed to anticipate and handle this race situation may then become unpredictable.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Such a risk may be overlooked for a long time in a system that seems very reliable.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] But eventually enough data may accumulate or enough other software may be added to critically destabilize many parts of a system.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] An example of this occurred with the near loss of the Mars Rover "Spirit" not long after landing, which occurred due to deleted file entries causing the file system library to consume all available memory space.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A solution is for software to request and reserve all the resources it will need before beginning a task; if this request fails then the task is postponed, avoiding the many points where failure could have occurred.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Alternatively, each of those points can be equipped with error handling, or the success of the entire task can be verified afterwards, before continuing.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A more common approach is to simply verify that enough system resources are available before starting a task; however, this may not be adequate because in complex systems the actions of other running programs can be unpredictable.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In networking, consider a distributed chat network like IRC, where a user who starts a channel automatically acquires channel-operator privileges.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] However, the latency across the network makes possible the kind of race condition described.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In this case, heading off race conditions by imposing a form of control over access to the shared resource—say, appointing one server to control who holds what privileges—would mean turning the distributed network into a centralized one (at least for that one part of the network operation).
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Race conditions can also exist when a computer program is written with non-blocking sockets, in which case the performance of the program can be dependent on the speed of the network link.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Software flaws in life-critical systems can be disastrous.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Race conditions were among the flaws in the Therac-25 radiation therapy machine, which led to the death of at least three patients and injuries to several more.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Another example is the energy management system provided by GE Energy and used by Ohio-based FirstEnergy Corp (among other power facilities).
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] A race condition existed in the alarm subsystem; when three sagging power lines were tripped simultaneously, the condition prevented alerts from being raised to the monitoring technicians, delaying their awareness of the problem.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] This software flaw eventually led to the North American Blackout of 2003.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] GE Energy later developed a software patch to correct the previously undiscovered error.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Many software tools exist to help detect race conditions in software.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] They can be largely categorized into two groups: static analysis tools and dynamic analysis tools.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Thread Safety Analysis is a static analysis tool for annotation-based intra-procedural static analysis, originally implemented as a branch of gcc, and now reimplemented in Clang, supporting PThreads.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Race conditions are a common concern in human-computer interaction design and software usability.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In UK railway signalling, a race condition would arise in the carrying out of Rule 55.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] According to this rule, if a train was stopped on a running line by a signal, the locomotive fireman would walk to the signal box in order to remind the signalman that the train was present.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] In at least one case, at Winwick in 1934, an accident occurred because the signalman accepted another train before the fireman arrived.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Modern signalling practice removes the race condition by making it possible for the driver to instantaneously contact the signal box by radio.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Race conditions are not confined to digital systems.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] Neuroscience is demonstrating that race conditions can occur in mammal brains as well.
[src:race-condition-security/race-condition] One demonstrated race is between neural pathways that execute planned movement and separate pathways that can cancel said movement.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In software development, **time-of-check to time-of-use** (**TOCTOU**, **TOCTTOU** or **TOC/TOU**) is a class of software bugs caused by a race condition involving the *checking* of the state of a part of a system (such as a security credential) and the *use* of the results of that check.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] TOCTOU race conditions are common in Unix between operations on the file system, but can occur in other contexts, including local sockets and improper use of database transactions.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In the early 1990s, the mail utility of BSD 4.3 UNIX had an exploitable race condition for temporary files because it used the `mktemp()` function.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Early versions of OpenSSH had an exploitable race condition for Unix domain sockets.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] They remain a problem in modern systems; as of 2019, a TOCTOU race condition in Docker allows root access to the filesystem of the host platform.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In the 2023 Pwn2Own competition in Vancouver, a team of hackers were able to compromise the gateway in an updated Tesla Model 3 using this bug.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In 2025, a TOCTOU race condition in Amazon Web Services' DNS management system for DynamoDB caused a major outage across the US-EAST-1 region.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] The incident stemmed from outdated DNS plans being applied after newer ones had already been cleaned up, resulting in the deletion of endpoint IP addresses and widespread service failure.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Then, if another process does in fact change the property between step 1 and 2, step 2 is performed based on outdated information, which can have unintended consequences.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] If the program running is privileged, and an unprivileged process can affect the property, it can effectively execute certain privileged tasks.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In particular, if the property checks whether some action is allowed, and thereby implements a security boundary, such as a permissions check, this permissions check can then be bypassed completely, and a variety of privileged actions can be executed this way (privilege escalation).
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Here, *access* is intended to check whether the real user who executed the `setuid` program would normally be allowed to write the file (i.e., `*access*` checks the real userid rather than effective userid).
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In this example, an attacker can exploit the race condition between the `access` and `open` to trick the `setuid` victim into overwriting an entry in the system password database.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] TOCTOU races can be used for privilege escalation to get administrative access to a machine.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Although this sequence of events requires precise timing, it is possible for an attacker to arrange such conditions without too much difficulty.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] The implication is that applications cannot assume the state managed by the operating system (in this case the file system namespace) will not change between system calls.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Exploiting a TOCTOU race condition requires precise timing to ensure that the attacker's operations interleave properly with the victim's.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In the example above, the attacker must execute the `symlink` system call precisely between the `access` and `open`.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] For the most general attack, the attacker must be scheduled for execution after each operation by the victim, also known as "single-stepping" the victim.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In the case of BSD 4.3 mail utility and `mktemp()`, the attacker can simply keep launching mail utility in one process, and keep guessing the temporary file names and keep making symlinks in another process.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] The attack can usually succeed in less than one minute.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Techniques for single-stepping a victim program include file system mazes and algorithmic complexity attacks.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In both cases, the attacker manipulates the OS state to control scheduling of the victim.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] File system mazes force the victim to read a directory entry that is not in the OS cache, and the OS puts the victim to sleep while it is reading the directory from disk.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Algorithmic complexity attacks force the victim to spend its entire scheduling quantum inside a single system call traversing the kernel's hash table of cached file names.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] The attacker creates a very large number of files with names that hash to the same value as the file the victim will look up.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Despite conceptual simplicity, TOCTOU race conditions are difficult to avoid and eliminate.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] One general technique is to use error handling instead of pre-checking, under the philosophy of EAFP – "It is easier to ask for forgiveness than permission" – rather than LBYL – "look before you leap".
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In this case there is no check, and failure of assumptions to hold are signaled by an error being returned.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In the context of file system TOCTOU race conditions, the fundamental challenge is ensuring that the file system cannot be changed between two system calls.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In 2004, an impossibility result was published, showing that there was no portable, deterministic technique for avoiding TOCTOU race conditions when using the Unix `access` and `open` filesystem calls.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Since this impossibility result, libraries for tracking file descriptors and ensuring correctness have been proposed by researchers.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] An alternative solution proposed in the research community is for Unix systems to adopt transactions in the file system or the OS kernel.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Transactions provide a concurrency control abstraction for the OS, and can be used to prevent TOCTOU races.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] While no production Unix kernel has yet adopted transactions, proof-of-concept research prototypes have been developed for Linux, including the Valor file system and the TxOS kernel.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Microsoft Windows has added transactions to its NTFS file system, but Microsoft discourages their use, and has indicated that they may be removed in a future version of Windows.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] File locking is a common technique for preventing race conditions for a single file, but it does not extend to the file system namespace and other metadata, nor does locking work well with networked filesystems, and cannot prevent TOCTOU race conditions.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] For `setuid` binaries, a possible solution is to use the `seteuid()` system call to change the effective user and then perform the `open()` call.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] Differences in `setuid()` between operating systems can be problematic.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] TOCTOU vulnerabilities have caused significant outages in large-scale systems.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] In October 2025, AWS experienced a major disruption due to a race condition in its DNS management system for DynamoDB.
[src:race-condition-security/time-of-check-to-time-of-use] The incident involved outdated DNS plans being applied after newer ones had already been cleaned up, leading to the deletion of endpoint IPs and widespread service failure.
